{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:18:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:18:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15670"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15670"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.79,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52514"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"},{"type":"tags","id":"10144"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ovaries are endocrine organs that produce several important hormones throughout the menstrual cycle and during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormones is released by the ovary?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Follicle stimulating hormone","Luteinising hormone","Oestrogen","Oxytocin","Relaxin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ovaries are responsible for producing several key hormones. \u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen\u003C/strong\u003E is produced by granulosa cells of developing follicles and the corpus luteum. The ovaries also produce progesterone (from the corpus luteum), inhibin (from granulosa cells), and small amounts of androgens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eluteinising hormone\u003C/strong\u003E are produced by the anterior pituitary gland, not the ovaries. \u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin\u003C/strong\u003E is produced by the hypothalamus and released by the posterior pituitary. \u003Cstrong\u003ERelaxin\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily produced by the corpus luteum during pregnancy and later by the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ovaries produce oestrogen, progesterone, inhibin, and small amounts of testosterone and androstenedione.","Relaxin is primarily produced by the corpus luteum during pregnancy and the placenta.","The anterior pituitary, not the ovaries, produces follicle stimulating hormone and luteinising hormone."],"references":["Richards JS, Pangas SA. The ovary: basic biology and clinical implications. J Clin Invest. 2010 Apr;120(4):963-72. doi: 10.1172/JCI41350. Epub 2010 Apr 1. PMID: 20364094; PMCID: PMC2846061.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15670"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52514"},